                            <comment id="72621" author="cbeams" created="Sat, 12 Nov 2011 17:09:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Julian,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is certainly possible to make the ResourceDatabasePopulator configurable through an EmbeddedDatabaseBuilder constructor argument.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is currently possible, as you may have noticed, to configure the statement separator using using ResourceDatabasePopulator#setSeparator&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As you mention, there is no way to tell the ResourceDatabasePopulator to consider the entire contents of the file as a single statement.  This could be added as a special kind of statement separator &amp;#8211; an &quot;EOF&quot; separator, if you will.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, even if we were to add this per-file statement separation, I&apos;m not sure that it would be useful in a general purpose way.  The reason for this is that there is only one ResourceDatabasePopluator in use for a given EmbeddedDatabaseBuilder, and if the statement separator is set to the special &quot;EOF&quot; value, this setting will apply to &lt;b&gt;all&lt;/b&gt; scripts added against the builder.  This is probably not what you (or others would want), am I correct?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What it seems that you want is to be able to specify the separator on a per-script basis, which is a less trivial change to introduce.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We could conceivably introduce another method altogether &amp;#8211; &apos;addStatement(String)&apos;.  This would allow a kind of escape hatch for cases like this.  You would have to deal with extracting the contents of the script file into a String, but once that is done, you could simply add it to the builder with no concern about statement separators, etc.  Any value added there is assumed to be a single statement.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This probably wouldn&apos;t be exposed through the jdbc: namespace, but would rather assume the user is programmatically configuring an EmbeddedDatabaseBuilder, e.g. within a @Bean method in a @Configuration class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please provide your thoughts on the above, thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="72639" author="golliwog" created="Mon, 14 Nov 2011 01:27:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Chris,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;What it seems that you want is to be able to specify the separator on a per-script basis, which is a less trivial change to introduce.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Yes, I thought that would be the easiest way. But with a closer look, it is not. It would be necessary to add the information of splitting(yes/no) to the Resource that encapsulates the script. The Resource-Interface does not provide the possibility to add any kind of metadata.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;The EOF-Separator is something that mysql uses. When creating a function, you have to specify the delimiter that ends the statement:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p/&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;syntaxplugin&quot; class=&quot;syntaxplugin&quot; style=&quot;border: 1px dashed #bbb; border-radius: 5px !important; overflow: auto; max-height: 30em;&quot;&gt;
&lt;table cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em !important; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; color: black;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;tbody &gt;
